04328nam a22006015i 9780520969193DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2017023359  a97805209691937 a10.1525/97805209691932doi  a(DE-B1597)519364  a(OCoLC)993878408  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aGN479.6b.E55 2017 4aGN479.6b.E556 2017 7aSOC0100002bisacsh04a305.422231 aEnloe, Cynthia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Big Push :bExposing and Challenging the Persistence of Patriarchy /cCynthia Enloe. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: It’s Not All About Trump -- t1. Pink Pussy Hats vs. Patriarchy -- t2. Syrian Women Resist Peace Table Patriarchy -- t3. When Carmen Miranda Returns -- t4. Tourism and Complicity at Ticonderoga, Gettysburg, and Hiroshima -- t5. Patriarchal Forgetting at Gallipoli, the Somme, and The Hague -- t6. A Flick of the Skirt -- t7. A Winding Road to Feminist Consciousness -- t8. Cafeteria Ladies, Wonder Woman at the UN, and Other Acts of Resistance -- tConclusion: Updated Patriarchy Is Not Invincible -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor over a century and in scores of countries, patriarchal presumptions and practices have been challenged by women and their male allies. “Sexual harassment” has entered common parlance; police departments are equipped with rape kits; more than half of the national legislators in Bolivia and Rwanda are women; and a woman candidate won the plurality of the popular votes in the 2016 United States presidential election. But have we really reached equality and overthrown a patriarchal point of view? The Big Push exposes how patriarchal ideas and relationships continue to be modernized to this day. Through contemporary cases and reports, renowned political scientist Cynthia Enloe exposes the workings of everyday patriarchy—in how Syrian women civil society activists have been excluded from international peace negotiations; how sexual harassment became institutionally accepted within major news organizations; or in how the UN Secretary General’s post has remained a masculine domain. Enloe then lays out strategies and skills for challenging patriarchal attitudes and operations. Encouraging self-reflection, she guides us in the discomforting curiosity of reviewing our own personal complicity in sustaining patriarchy in order to withdraw our own support for it. Timely and globally conscious, The Big Push is a call for feminist self-reflection and strategic action with a belief that exposure complements resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminismxSocial conditions. 0aPatriarchyxHistory. 0aPatriarchyxSocial aspectszSyria. 0aPatriarchy. 0aSex role. 0aSexual harassment. 0aWomenxEconomic conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066755440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520969193?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520969193423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520969193/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles